"Just as you please; I'm sorry I cant spare ye a tablecloth for a mattress, and it's a plaguy rough board here"--feeling of the knots and notches.  As I live, these covered parts of him were checkered with the same squares as his face; his back, too, was all over the same dark squares; he seemed to have been in a Thirty Years' War, and just escaped from it with a sticking-plaster shirt. 

"I thought so. 

I told him that I never liked to sleep two in a bed; that if I should ever do so, it would depend upon who the harpooneer might be, and that if he (the landlord) really had no other place for me, and the harpooneer was not decidedly objectionable, why rather than wander further about a strange town on so bitter a night, I would put up with the half of any decent man's blanket.  He was trying his hand at a ship under full sail, but he didn't make much headway, I thought.  But stop; does it not bear a faint resemblance to a gigantic fish?  What's all this fuss I have been making about, thought I to myself--the man's a human being just as I am: he has just as much reason to fear me, as I have to be afraid of him.  I s'pose you are goin' a-whalin', so you'd better get used to that sort of thing." 

"It's broke a'ready," said he. 

"Me sabbee plenty"--grunted Queequeg, puffing away at his pipe and sitting up in bed. 

"There," said the landlord, placing the candle on a crazy old sea chest that did double duty as a wash-stand and centre table; "there, make yourself comfortable now, and good night to ye." 

"Stop your grinning," shouted I, "and why didn't you tell me that that infernal harpooneer was a cannibal?" 

"With heads to be sure; ain't there too many heads in the world?" 

