"Landlord!  I sought the landlord, and telling him I desired to be accommodated with a room, received for answer that his house was full--not a bed unoccupied.  I began to twitch all over.  Suppose now, he should tumble in upon me at midnight--how could I tell from what vile hole he had been coming?  Yet was there a sort of indefinite, half-attained, unimaginable sublimity about it that fairly froze you to it, till you involuntarily took an oath with yourself to find out what that marvellous painting meant.  The next moment the light was extinguished, and this wild cannibal, tomahawk between his teeth, sprang into bed with me.  I was all eagerness to see his face, but he kept it averted for some time while employed in unlacing the bag's mouth.  "Landlord!  I come to your house and want a bed; you tell me you can only give me half a one; that the other half belongs to a certain harpooneer.  It seemed no bad idea; but upon second thoughts I dismissed it.  But then, what to make of his unearthly complexion, that part of it, I mean, lying round about, and completely independent of the squares of tattooing.  It was of a dark, purplish, yellow colour, here and there stuck over with large blackish looking squares. 

